1️⃣ Variables (How Computer Stores Data)
Simple Idea

A variable is a named box that stores data.

Real-World Example

Think of a locker in a gym:

Locker number → variable name

Items inside → data

Locker A → Shoes  
Locker B → Phone  

In C++:

int age = 20;

age → locker name

20 → value inside

What Happens Inside the Computer

When you write:

int age = 20;

Computer does 3 things:

Finds some memory space (RAM)

Stores value 20

Labels it as age

Why Variables Exist

Without variables:

cout << 20;
cout << 20 + 5;

No reuse.

With variables:

int age = 20;
cout << age;
cout << age + 5;

👉 Reusability + clarity

Mental Model (Never Forget)

Think:

Variable = Label + Storage

OR

Name → points to a memory box
Connection to What You Already Know

In C / Java, same concept exists

Only syntax slightly changes

Example Java:

int age = 20;

👉 Same as C++

Common Mistake (Important for Placements)
int age;
cout << age;  // ❌ garbage value

Why?

Because no value assigned yet.

👉 Always initialize variables.

How to Remember (No Cramming)

Ask yourself:

“If I don’t name the data, how will I reuse it?”

That’s why variables exist.

2️⃣ Data Types (How Memory is Organized)
Simple Idea

Data type tells:

👉 What kind of data
👉 How much memory to allocate

Real-World Example

Think of containers:

Container	Use
Bottle	Liquid
Box	Solid
Envelope	Paper

Similarly:

Data Type	Stores
int	integers
float	decimals
char	single character
Example
int age = 20;
float price = 99.5;
char grade = 'A';
Why Data Types Matter

Computer memory is limited.

So it asks:

“How much space should I give?”

What Happens Internally
int age = 20;

Allocates 4 bytes

Stores value 20

char grade = 'A';

Allocates 1 byte

Mental Model

Think:

Data type = size + meaning

OR

Container decides what you can store
Key Data Types (Placement Important)
Type	Size	Example
int	4 bytes	10
float	4 bytes	10.5
double	8 bytes	10.12345
char	1 byte	'A'
bool	1 byte	true/false
Connection to Real Life

You don’t store water in a paper bag.

Similarly:

int x = 10.5;  // ❌ data loss

👉 Wrong container → wrong result

Why It Works

Because memory is structured.

Computer needs:

fixed size

fixed format

to work efficiently.

Common Interview Insight 🔥
int x = 10.9;
cout << x;

Output?

👉 10

Why?

Because:

int cannot store decimal

it truncates (cuts off)

How to Remember Forever

Ask:

“What kind of data am I storing?”

That automatically tells:

variable type

memory size

🔥 Mini Practice (Very Important)

Predict output:

int a = 10;
float b = 5.5;

cout << a + b;

👉 Think before answering.

